Correct Ans: All of the above. `x` is an S3 object. S3 is an OOP system in R. R has many OOP system like R6, S4. S3 objects have `class` attribute. `class()` returns a character vector of classes. You can overwrite the `class` #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:12122021220046]

[see_image_2] When you check the class of an object. The returned vector tells you the inherited classes and their order of inheritance. So in the below example, "factor" is the base class and "ordered" has inherited from "factor" #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:12122021220046] https://t.co/4claoQ62bi

*do you like programming in #RStats?*
Me: https://t.co/MBB80ggSDj

generics use the class name to find a function associated with that particular class (method) and executes it. For example, In the given image, when the 1st `print()` is called, `print()` tries to search for a function #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:12122021220046]

attribute, often times leading to unintended behaviour, S3 doesn't have any checks to prevent you from doing that. [see_image_1] To create an object of certain class, you can assign by using `class()` or using `structure()`. #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:12122021220046] https://t.co/HFEq00oWAc

or in other words, "factor" is the super class & "ordered" is the sub class. [see_image_3] The order of inheritance is used when the object is passed to generic functions like `print()`, `plot()`, `summary()`.
